In a stunning turn of events, Robert Durst, the scion of a New York real estate fortune, was arrested in New Orleans late Saturday in connection with a first-degree murder warrant from Los Angeles County. 

The arrest comes as authorities were interviewing new witnesses in the 2000 slaying of a Los Angeles writer, Susan Berman. Berman and Durst were friends, and detectives have long sought to interview him about the case. Durst spoke at length about the case in an HBO documentary series now airing, which included new evidence about the slaying. Read more: http://fw.to/EKmvOKc

Blurred lines, indeed. In classical music it’s even blurrier, music critic Mark Swed writes, and proud to be. The kind of “borrowing” that a judge ruled was copying this week in a trial concerning the hit 2013 song "Blurred Lines," has been commonplace – at one point, even preferable to original music – for centuries.

"In the mist of a fountain by the San Diego waterfront park, a guy dropped to one knee at CRSSD festival and asked his love to marry him. The crowd of be-tank-topped San Diego EDM dudes cheered as he embraced his beloved and she said yes, yes, yes," writes August Brown. 

"That was the mood at the opening day of CRSSD, a new dance music festival produced under the auspices of Goldenvoice but geared toward the mass of dance music fans looking for what happens after festival rave."

http://www.latimes.com/opinion/editorials/la-ed-iran-letter-20150311-story.html
Yes, The Times' editorial board thought it was OK for then-Speaker Nancy Pelosi and three of her Republican colleagues to go to Syria in 2007 to meet with President Assad (http://articles.latimes.com/2007/apr/04/opinion/ed-pelosi04). But meetings between lawmakers and foreign heads of state (even hostile ones) aren't unusual, as the board notes here and in that editorial. Having senators intervene in negotiations between the White House and a foreign government, on the other hand, is a whole 'nother kettle of fish.
post content:  http://www.latimes.com/opinion/editorials/la-ed-iran-letter-20150311-story.html Yes, The Times' editorial board thought it was OK for then-Speaker Nancy Pelosi and three of her Republican colleagues to go to Syria in 2007 to meet with President Assad (http://articles.latimes.com/2007/apr/04/opinion/ed-pelosi04). But meetings between lawmakers and foreign heads of state (even hostile ones) aren't unusual, as the board notes here and in that editorial. Having senators intervene in negotiations between the White House and a foreign government, on the other hand, is a whole 'nother kettle of fish.

Presumptive Democratic presidential front-runner Hillary Clinton is in the spotlight this week, after reports that she used a private email account during her time as Secretary of State. Critics say it’s a potential violation of federal law, and have raised questions over Clinton’s motives in keeping emails off of government servers. In her first response since the scandal broke, Clinton says she’s asked the State Department to make thousands of those personal emails public. We’ll discuss the Clinton controversy, and what it could mean for her 2016 chances, exclusively with former Arkansas Governor Mike Huckabee (R).

After weeks of political infighting and cross-party jabs, the House and Senate are expected to approve a short-term spending bill that would avoid a shutdown of the Department of Homeland Security. However, the stopgap measure would simply punt the issue for another three weeks, and DHS Secretary Jeh Johnson has voiced frustration that a long-term solution has not been reached. We’ll talk exclusively with the Majority Whip, Rep Steve Scalise (R-LA) who is responsible for “whipping up” votes for his party in the House.
